widgets_values: A highly detailed, cinematic portrait of a young woman standing confidently against a softly blurred urban backdrop at twilight, captured from a low-angle perspective emphasizing her full height (5'8") and elegant proportions with balanced facial features. She faces the camera directly with a subtle, serene smile, head slightly tilted to her right, left hand resting gently on her hip while her right arm hangs naturally by her side. Her outfit consists of a tailored ivory silk blouse with delicate lace trim at the cuffs and collar, paired with high-waisted black wool trousers featuring a subtle pinstripe pattern; she wears minimalist gold hoop earrings and polished nude pumps. The lighting is soft, diffused Rembrandt lighting from the left at 30Â° angle, casting gentle shadows on her right cheekbone while illuminating her hair's natural wave texture with warm amber tones; ambient city glow creates a subtle lens flare effect in the upper-left corner. Shot with an 85mm prime lens at f/1.8 for shallow depth of field, showcasing crisp skin texture and fabric details against a bokeh background of muted teal building facades and distant streetlights. Style: Photorealistic film photography with Kodak Portra 400 grain emulation, natural skin tones, and cinematic color grading emphasizing cool blues in shadows versus warm golds in highlights. Maintain exact pose symmetry, outfit material textures (silk sheen on blouse, wool nap on trousers), and lighting physics as depicted.

This workflow demonstrates how to define a custom style by connecting through the "customization" input in the "Style & Prompt Encoder" node.

A multi-line string must be defined using the following format:
Each line starting with ">>>" (three greater-than signs) defines the name of the style. From there, all subsequent lines until the next ">>>" define the content of that style. Within this content, the tag "{$@}" will be replaced by the prompt.

While the example shows all styles being defined as "Custom <N>", this method can be used to redefine any of the available styles in the style selector.
